               <head>Akbarnāmah. Vol. 1 by Abū al-Faz̤l ibn Mubārak</head>

               <msContents class="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n80002413
                  http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh85064913
                  http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2008115921
                  http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh2008115920">

                  <summary>Volume I, a slightly defective copy of the <title>Akbarnāmah</title> comprising Book I
                     in two parts. </summary>

                  <msItem xml:id="Uk_IO_Islamic_1-item1">
                     <author key="viaf_5150639">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Abū al-Faz̤l ibn Mubārak,
                           1551-1602</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">أبو الفضل بن مبارك</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20880">Akbarnāmah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa">اكبرنامه</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="basmala">(f.1v) الله اكبر اين چه دريافتيست
                        الخ</incipit>
                     <note>
                        <p>The first part of the first book is dated 1111 AH (1699/1700). </p>
                        <p>The second part begins on f. 235v and is incomplete, breaking off in the
                              <hi rend="italic">khātimah</hi> on f. 531r with the words <foreign
                              xml:lang="per">مرا زندگ</foreign>. </p>
                        <p>ٔFolios 527–531 have been added subsequently. </p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <extent>ff. 531 <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>375</height>
                              <width>184</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>
                           <p>European numerals stamped on recto. </p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation>
                           <p>
                              <catchwords>Catchwords on the bottom-left corners of the verso.
                              </catchwords>
                           </p>
                        </collation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>Fair.n</p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="19">
                           <p>19 lines per page. </p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <summary/>
                     <handNote>
                        <p>Large clear nastaʻlīq; copied in black ink, with headings and overlinings
                           in red. </p>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <p>Note in Persian on f. 1r by former owner <persName key="viaf_57907434"
                           role="fmo">Lachhmī Narāyan Shafīq Awrangābādī (b. 1745)</persName>,
                        saying that the manuscript was acquired 25 Jumadi I 1177 (1 Dec 1763) via
                        Ḥājjī Sulṭān <hi rend="italic">saḥḥāf</hi>, accompanied by his oval seal. </p>
                     <p>Note in Persian, presumably by Richard Johnson's munshi, recording purchase
                        in Hyderbabad as one of 11 vols for RS 500. </p>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1900" notAfter="1950">
                        <decoNote>Half-leather early twentieth-century red India Office Library
                           binding. </decoNote>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <seal subtype="oval" type="stamp">
                        <p>Oval seal of former owner (f. 1r): <hi rend="italic"><persName
                                 key="viaf57907434" role="fmo">Shafīq</persName> 1178</hi>
                           (1764/65). </p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal subtype="oval" type="stamp">
                        <p>Oval stamp (ff. 1r, 531v): ‘EI Company Library’. </p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin><origDate calendar="Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1669" notAfter="1670">1111 AH
                        (1699-70 CE)</origDate>
                     <origPlace>India</origPlace>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Acquired by <persName key="viaf_57907434"
                           role="fmo">Lachhmī Narāyan Shafīq Awrangābādī</persName> from the bookseller Ḥājjī
                        Sulṭān on 25 Jumadi I, 1177 (1 Dec 1763) with IO Islamic 2 and 6, as part
                        of a 3 vol. set costing RS 157 (see IO Islamic 6). </p>
                     <p>Subsequently sold to <persName role="fmo" key="viaf_287207857">Richard
                           Johnson</persName>, East India Company Resident in Hyderabad 1784-5, for RS 500 as one
                        of 11 mss. </p>
                  </provenance>

                  <acquisition>
                     <p>The Johnson collection—comprising 64 albums of paintings and an estimated
                        1,000 manuscripts—was purchased by the East India Company Library for 3,000
                        guineas on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1807-02-18">18 February
                           1807</date>. </p>
                  </acquisition>

               </history>
